(& its extremely baby brained to believe that every time someone accused of something is acquitted then they did not do it. Literal murderers have been acquitted of their earlier crimes before standing trial for a later murder and it finally being proved beyond reasonable doubt)
Making false accusations a crime would just mean that even more people will not come forward, because if they lose their case they will end up in court themselves.

Being acquitted can mean the jury believes you did not commit the crime of which you are accused, but you can also be acquitted in the event that the jury strongly suspects you are guilty BUT they are not satisfied that your guilt has been proven beyond reasonable doubt.

"Making false accusations of rape should be punishable by law", ok so how do you determine if an accusation was false? Is it if the accused is acquitted? Because I've got news for you - acquittal does not automatically equal innocence
